WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.660 --> 00:00:04.426
PROFESSOR: So what I would like
you to do is to answer

00:00:04.426 --> 00:00:06.580
the following question.

00:00:06.580 --> 00:00:10.035
"Do you have..?" oh, now
wait a second -- this

00:00:10.035 --> 00:00:11.880
says polling closed.

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:14.181
Let's see whether we can
get polling to open.

00:00:14.181 --> 00:00:16.090
Do you...?" -No, that
didn't work.

00:00:16.090 --> 00:00:18.250
Oh, this is the most desperately
horrible thing

00:00:18.250 --> 00:00:19.550
that I've ever had happen.

00:00:19.550 --> 00:00:20.360
OK.

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:21.990
Current slide.

00:00:21.990 --> 00:00:23.235
I've had horrible things happen
that are worse than

00:00:23.235 --> 00:00:25.118
this, I'm sorry.

00:00:25.118 --> 00:00:27.586
I don't want to belittle all
the really horrible things

00:00:27.586 --> 00:00:28.504
that have ever happened to me.

00:00:28.504 --> 00:00:29.070
[laughter]

00:00:29.070 --> 00:00:29.780
OK.

00:00:29.780 --> 00:00:31.850
So let's try again.

00:00:31.850 --> 00:00:33.500
Click practicalities
blah blah.

00:00:33.500 --> 00:00:36.060
OK. "Do you have
a clicker yet?

00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:39.460
Polling is open." OK.

00:00:39.460 --> 00:00:41.512
And there's ten seconds left.

00:00:41.512 --> 00:00:43.123
You'll see this little
timeline.

00:00:43.123 --> 00:00:46.765
Eight, seven, six, five, four--
ninety two of you, so

00:00:46.765 --> 00:00:48.530
many of you have clickers.

00:00:48.530 --> 00:00:48.740
OK.

00:00:48.740 --> 00:00:51.810
Let's see what we learned.

00:00:51.810 --> 00:00:57.313
It looks like 97% of
you have clickers.

00:00:57.313 --> 00:00:59.360
[laughter]

00:00:59.360 --> 00:01:00.800
Now!

00:01:00.800 --> 00:01:07.310
I actually began with this
exercise to make a point about

00:01:07.310 --> 00:01:10.625
psychological research.

00:01:10.625 --> 00:01:19.060
We just made a classic and
dangerous mistake, a mistake

00:01:19.060 --> 00:01:20.944
known as sampling bias.

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:28.970
We used a measure which doesn't
give us accurate

00:01:28.970 --> 00:01:31.390
information about what we
wanted to find out.

00:01:31.390 --> 00:01:35.007
We wanted to find out, what
percentage of people in the

00:01:35.007 --> 00:01:37.480
room had clickers.

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:40.482
And what we found out instead
was, what percentage of people

00:01:40.482 --> 00:01:43.607
in the room with clickers
had clickers.

00:01:43.607 --> 00:01:45.305
[laughter]

00:01:45.305 --> 00:01:46.555
I don't know who you guys are.

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:53.831
This error is an incredibly
dangerous one, and it could

00:01:53.831 --> 00:01:55.004
have persisted.

00:01:55.004 --> 00:01:58.030
Suppose I then ask you a
question whether you're from

00:01:58.030 --> 00:02:04.072
the class of 2014, '13, '12,
or '11, and discovered that

00:02:04.072 --> 00:02:08.380
80% of you were freshmen
and sophomores.

00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:12.326
There, then, I would inherited
exactly the sampling bias

00:02:12.326 --> 00:02:15.900
error that we just observed.

00:02:15.900 --> 00:02:18.063
Freshmen and sophomores
have handed in

00:02:18.063 --> 00:02:19.970
their schedules already.

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:22.000
Consequently, they're
certain about what

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:23.330
classes they're taking.

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:25.815
Consequently, they're
more likely to

00:02:25.815 --> 00:02:28.624
have clickers already.

00:02:28.624 --> 00:02:34.990
So when we do psychological
empirical research, we need to

00:02:34.990 --> 00:02:39.308
be extraordinarily careful that
the means by which we are

00:02:39.308 --> 00:02:44.550
choosing subjects for
experiments are, in fact,

00:02:44.550 --> 00:02:50.400
means that give us an accurate
sample of what it is that

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:52.844
we're interested in.

00:02:52.844 --> 00:02:56.940
An article appeared recently in
the journal Behavioral and

00:02:56.940 --> 00:03:01.310
Brain Sciences with the
title, "The Weirdest

00:03:01.310 --> 00:03:05.180
People in the World".

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:13.080
And "WEIRD" here stands
for Western, educated,

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:17.154
industrialized, rich,
and democratic.

00:03:17.154 --> 00:03:22.173
That is, American college
students.

00:03:22.173 --> 00:03:28.020
People with access to online
Internet polling.

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:33.660
And what the article argued
was that a great deal of

00:03:33.660 --> 00:03:39.870
psychological research that
claims to make general

00:03:39.870 --> 00:03:42.715
assumptions, that claims to
prove general assumptions

00:03:42.715 --> 00:03:50.250
about human nature, is biased
in exactly the way my poll

00:03:50.250 --> 00:03:54.280
concerning what percentage of
you have clickers was biased.

00:03:54.280 --> 00:04:00.490
It looks at a small sample of
the population, those who are

00:04:00.490 --> 00:04:04.900
readily available to research
laboratories on university

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:10.882
campuses, for example, the psych
introductory psych pool.

00:04:10.882 --> 00:04:14.500
And it bases its conclusions
about human

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:19.210
nature on that sample.

00:04:19.210 --> 00:04:23.676
Throughout the semester we need
to be attentive, when we

00:04:23.676 --> 00:04:26.470
read psychological studies which
are making claims about

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:32.170
human nature, to the fact that
it is possible that some of

00:04:32.170 --> 00:04:35.955
the things which we are told
apply to human beings in

00:04:35.955 --> 00:04:42.750
general instead have at least
being shown conclusively only

00:04:42.750 --> 00:04:46.580
to apply to WEIRD folk.

00:04:46.580 --> 00:04:49.386
Western, educated,
industrialized, rich, and

00:04:49.386 --> 00:04:51.250
democratic.

00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:56.430
And in certain cases, the data
would look very different if

00:04:56.430 --> 00:05:01.066
we looked at a different
population.

00:05:01.066 --> 00:05:05.962
This is also the case in the
classical texts we used.

00:05:05.962 --> 00:05:11.230
The process that Plato and
Aristotle took on for

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:14.715
themselves didn't look
experimental in the way that

00:05:14.715 --> 00:05:17.770
experimental psychology
looks experimental.

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:22.880
But they looked at a sample of
people around them, and on the

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:27.410
basis of their experience, they
drew conclusions about

00:05:27.410 --> 00:05:30.110
human nature.

00:05:30.110 --> 00:05:34.285
So little reminder of something
that I said in the

00:05:34.285 --> 00:05:39.728
first lecture that sometimes
gets lost. In some ways, this

00:05:39.728 --> 00:05:41.673
is a class about philosophy
and the

00:05:41.673 --> 00:05:43.645
science of human nature.

00:05:43.645 --> 00:05:48.244
And in other ways, this is a
class about Western philosophy

00:05:48.244 --> 00:05:52.020
and the science of Western
human nature.

00:05:52.020 --> 00:05:58.494
And we need to be attentive to
that when it becomes relevant.

00:05:58.494 --> 00:06:03.740
So what I want to do in today's
lecture is to return

00:06:03.740 --> 00:06:08.820
to the issue that we took up
last class, which is the issue

00:06:08.820 --> 00:06:13.934
about the multi-part nature
of the human soul.

00:06:13.934 --> 00:06:16.940
And you'll recall that in the
last lecture, we were

00:06:16.940 --> 00:06:22.464
introduced to Plato's great
analogy of rational spirit and

00:06:22.464 --> 00:06:28.392
appetite, as exemplified by a
charioteer, a calm horse and a

00:06:28.392 --> 00:06:29.610
wild horse.

00:06:29.610 --> 00:06:34.300
And also to a number of
other distinctions.

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:37.865
Left brain, right brain, which
I managed to get wrong four

00:06:37.865 --> 00:06:41.650
times in a row, if I
remember correctly.

00:06:41.650 --> 00:06:44.930
We were introduced to the
difference between brainstem

00:06:44.930 --> 00:06:46.460
and upper brain.

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:49.310
We were briefly introduced
to Freud's idea of

00:06:49.310 --> 00:06:52.400
superego, ego, and id.

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:57.580
But we didn't get to work in the
dual processing tradition.

00:06:57.580 --> 00:07:01.292
And today's lecture will take up
where the last lecture left

00:07:01.292 --> 00:07:05.940
off, with another way in which
it is typical to distinguish

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:07.830
parts of the soul.

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:11.780
Let me say that there is very
good reason to think that the

00:07:11.780 --> 00:07:16.530
research which I'm presenting
today is not subject to the

00:07:16.530 --> 00:07:18.854
WEIRD objection.

00:07:18.854 --> 00:07:21.190
That is, there have been
powerful cross-cultural

00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:24.462
demonstrations of nearly all
the results which I'll be

00:07:24.462 --> 00:07:26.080
talking about today.

00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:29.930
And there are also good
evolutionary reasons to think

00:07:29.930 --> 00:07:34.510
that the two systems which dual
systems theorists posit

00:07:34.510 --> 00:07:39.100
are, in fact, going to be part
of any human being because of

00:07:39.100 --> 00:07:43.800
the evolutionary process, which
all of us underwent.

00:07:43.800 --> 00:07:48.545
So I wanted to start with a
picture of Edward Thorndike

00:07:48.545 --> 00:07:51.446
not because he's important,
but just because he's so

00:07:51.446 --> 00:07:53.398
fabulous-looking.

00:07:53.398 --> 00:07:57.444
This is from the New York
Public Library Archive.

00:07:57.444 --> 00:08:02.970
Edward Thorndike was a late
19th, early 20th century

00:08:02.970 --> 00:08:07.640
psychologist who did a lot of
important associationist

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:09.670
animal work.

00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:15.510
But he also did research,
publishing an article in 1922,

00:08:15.510 --> 00:08:21.610
that in some ways can be seen
as the founding work of the

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:25.510
reasoning tradition that
Jonathan Evans described in

00:08:25.510 --> 00:08:29.405
the article that we read
for last class.

00:08:29.405 --> 00:08:35.340
So he describes, in his 1922
article, an experiment that he

00:08:35.340 --> 00:08:39.935
does, which is titled "The
Effect of Changed Data Upon

00:08:39.935 --> 00:08:41.144
Reasoning".

00:08:41.144 --> 00:08:45.440
And what he's interested in
there is the question of

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:50.180
whether problems that are
posed to people that are

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:54.910
formally identical, but that
differ in how that formal

00:08:54.910 --> 00:09:00.140
material is presented, are
processed differently.

00:09:00.140 --> 00:09:05.275
So, for example, he asked
people, either what is the

00:09:05.275 --> 00:09:08.963
square of x plus y, (first,
outer, inner, last, I think is

00:09:08.963 --> 00:09:15.126
how you would do it) and he
asked people, what is the

00:09:15.126 --> 00:09:18.930
square of b1 plus b2?

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:23.150
Whereas people found the first
question easy, they found the

00:09:23.150 --> 00:09:25.482
second question much
more difficult.

00:09:25.482 --> 00:09:28.892
Success rates on this
were up around 90%.

00:09:28.892 --> 00:09:31.520
Success rates on this were
considerably lower.

00:09:31.520 --> 00:09:36.080
Or he asked them, what's the
square of a squared x cubed,

00:09:36.080 --> 00:09:40.146
versus what's the square of
r subscript 1 to the 8th r

00:09:40.146 --> 00:09:42.780
subscript 11 to the second?

00:09:42.780 --> 00:09:45.016
And so on.

00:09:45.016 --> 00:09:48.910
Presenting people with problems
that were formally

00:09:48.910 --> 00:09:53.250
identical but which differed in
terms of the complexity of

00:09:53.250 --> 00:09:58.082
the characters used to represent
them produced a

00:09:58.082 --> 00:10:00.550
massive decrement
in performance.

00:10:03.202 --> 00:10:09.692
Fast forward to a period in the
1960s, '70s, and '80s, in

00:10:09.692 --> 00:10:14.959
which people began to study
syllogistic reasoning, and a

00:10:14.959 --> 00:10:21.180
number of special instances
of this phenomenon emerge.

00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:25.770
So in Jonathan Evans piece that
you read for last class,

00:10:25.770 --> 00:10:29.052
you were presented with
examples like this.

00:10:29.052 --> 00:10:35.784
A syllogism that was valid and
believable - that is, whose

00:10:35.784 --> 00:10:39.102
formal properties guaranteed
that if the premises were

00:10:39.102 --> 00:10:42.624
true, the conclusion was true,
and as a matter of fact

00:10:42.624 --> 00:10:45.084
conclusion was true.

00:10:45.084 --> 00:10:49.940
And arguments that were valid
but unbelievable--arguments

00:10:49.940 --> 00:10:52.706
where the structure of the
argument guaranteed that if

00:10:52.706 --> 00:10:56.160
the premises were true, the
conclusion was true, but where

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:59.130
the conclusion was false.

00:10:59.130 --> 00:11:02.120
So, for example, you might
be told: No Greek

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:05.450
tragedies are comedies.

00:11:05.450 --> 00:11:09.185
Some Greek comedies are plays.

00:11:09.185 --> 00:11:12.760
And asked whether it followed
from that that some Greek

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:14.900
plays are not Greek tragedies.

00:11:14.900 --> 00:11:17.838
No Greek tragedies are comedies,
some Greek plays are

00:11:17.838 --> 00:11:20.850
comedies, therefore, some Greek
plays are not Greek

00:11:20.850 --> 00:11:25.560
tragedies, and 90% of people
were able to see that that

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:28.020
argument was valid.

00:11:28.020 --> 00:11:31.180
By contrast, you might be given
an argument, equally

00:11:31.180 --> 00:11:35.180
valid, but with an unbelievable
conclusion; like:

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:37.840
No Russian novels are short.

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:40.670
Some novels by Dostoevsky
are short.

00:11:40.670 --> 00:11:42.960
Therefore, some novels
by Dostoevsky

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:44.320
are not Russian novels.

00:11:44.320 --> 00:11:45.550
That's a valid argument.

00:11:45.550 --> 00:11:48.405
It's a valid argument with a
false conclusion, because one

00:11:48.405 --> 00:11:51.827
of the premises is false.

00:11:51.827 --> 00:11:56.460
But as a result of the
conclusion being implausible,

00:11:56.460 --> 00:12:02.532
only 55% of people were able
to recognize that the

00:12:02.532 --> 00:12:05.970
conclusion followed
from the premises.

00:12:05.970 --> 00:12:12.813
Notice, however, that these
two arguments are

00:12:12.813 --> 00:12:13.695
structurally identical.

00:12:13.695 --> 00:12:19.220
They both have a form, no A's
are B's, some C's are B's,

00:12:19.220 --> 00:12:23.520
therefore, some C's
are not A's.

00:12:23.520 --> 00:12:28.174
Formal properties alone
don't determine our

00:12:28.174 --> 00:12:31.956
ability to judge validity.

00:12:31.956 --> 00:12:39.030
And, in fact, it is also true
that formal properties alone

00:12:39.030 --> 00:12:44.390
don't determine our ability
to judge invalidity.

00:12:44.390 --> 00:12:48.240
So whereas valid arguments with
plausible conclusions are

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:52.330
judged to be valid roughly 90%
of the time, we just heard

00:12:52.330 --> 00:12:56.410
that valid arguments with
implausible conclusions are

00:12:56.410 --> 00:12:59.943
judged to be valid considerably
less often.

00:12:59.943 --> 00:13:05.914
An opposite error arises in the
case of invalid arguments.

00:13:05.914 --> 00:13:09.790
Invalid arguments with plausible
conclusions are

00:13:09.790 --> 00:13:12.520
judged to be valid.

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:16.900
It's judged to be the case that
the form of the argument

00:13:16.900 --> 00:13:20.150
guarantees the truth
of the conclusion.

00:13:20.150 --> 00:13:23.140
Whereas it turns out that what
guarantees the truth of the

00:13:23.140 --> 00:13:26.980
conclusion, in that case, is
nothing other than facts about

00:13:26.980 --> 00:13:29.574
the world, as opposed
to facts about the

00:13:29.574 --> 00:13:33.035
structure of the argument.

00:13:33.035 --> 00:13:41.632
In light of this Thorndikean
condition, researcher after

00:13:41.632 --> 00:13:46.557
researcher came up with research
paradigms that

00:13:46.557 --> 00:13:51.640
demonstrated what we've just
been talking about.

00:13:51.640 --> 00:13:59.466
So, famously, the Wason
selection task asks people to

00:13:59.466 --> 00:14:04.733
determine which of four cards
they need to turn over to

00:14:04.733 --> 00:14:06.580
verify the truth
of a statement.

00:14:06.580 --> 00:14:09.205
So, for example, I might give
you a statement, "if there's

00:14:09.205 --> 00:14:13.867
an A on the one side, there's
a three on the other." And I

00:14:13.867 --> 00:14:17.330
might present you with four
cards, and ask you which ones

00:14:17.330 --> 00:14:19.530
you need to turn over.

00:14:19.530 --> 00:14:22.620
Obviously, you need to turn
over the A, and everybody

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:23.780
recognizes that.

00:14:23.780 --> 00:14:25.910
You need to check whether
there's a three

00:14:25.910 --> 00:14:27.644
on the other side.

00:14:27.644 --> 00:14:31.935
Obviously, you don't need to
turn over the D. You know that

00:14:31.935 --> 00:14:34.130
the cards have a letter
on one side, and a

00:14:34.130 --> 00:14:35.450
number on the other.

00:14:35.450 --> 00:14:37.891
So there's no worry that
there's an A on the

00:14:37.891 --> 00:14:39.695
other side of here.

00:14:39.695 --> 00:14:43.805
But people have a tendency to
think that you need to turn

00:14:43.805 --> 00:14:46.920
over the three, and that
you don't need to

00:14:46.920 --> 00:14:48.610
turn over the seven.

00:14:48.610 --> 00:14:50.910
But look out.

00:14:50.910 --> 00:14:55.280
Right on that other side of the
seven was an A. and the

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:58.824
statement turns out
to be false.

00:14:58.824 --> 00:15:04.440
The ones you need to check
are the A and the seven.

00:15:04.440 --> 00:15:09.450
People find this task relatively
difficult.

00:15:09.450 --> 00:15:13.370
But here's a structurally
identical task that people

00:15:13.370 --> 00:15:15.650
find relatively easy.

00:15:15.650 --> 00:15:21.390
"If a person is drinking beer,
the person must be over 21." I

00:15:21.390 --> 00:15:23.460
show you four cards.

00:15:23.460 --> 00:15:28.660
The beer drinker, the soda
drinker, the over-21 year old,

00:15:28.660 --> 00:15:31.478
and the 17 year old.

00:15:31.478 --> 00:15:34.766
And every single one of you
could I take it get a job as a

00:15:34.766 --> 00:15:40.070
bouncer, walk in, discover
that the 17 year old is

00:15:40.070 --> 00:15:42.480
drinking a beer.

00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:46.290
And thereby, learn exactly
what was hard to see in

00:15:46.290 --> 00:15:50.040
earlier case, that the cards you
need to turn over are the

00:15:50.040 --> 00:15:57.806
first and the last, rather than
the first and the third.

00:15:57.806 --> 00:16:02.502
Now, there have been all sorts
of explanations hypothesized

00:16:02.502 --> 00:16:06.590
for why it is that we find the
second of these tasks easier

00:16:06.590 --> 00:16:11.460
than the first. Perhaps the
most famous of these is a

00:16:11.460 --> 00:16:15.030
hypothesis advanced by the
evolutionary psychologists

00:16:15.030 --> 00:16:20.430
Leda Cosmides and John Tooby,
who argue that we have within

00:16:20.430 --> 00:16:25.295
ourselves what they call a
cheater detection module, and

00:16:25.295 --> 00:16:28.528
that we're enormously sensitive
to cases that

00:16:28.528 --> 00:16:33.874
involve violations of
normative rules.

00:16:33.874 --> 00:16:38.876
So you notice that the second
one is different from the

00:16:38.876 --> 00:16:41.530
first in two ways.

00:16:41.530 --> 00:16:45.790
One is that it's socially
embedded, whereas the first is

00:16:45.790 --> 00:16:46.660
purely abstract.

00:16:46.660 --> 00:16:50.114
And we'll discover, as we
continue our readings this

00:16:50.114 --> 00:16:55.410
semester, that social embedding
awakens reasoning

00:16:55.410 --> 00:16:58.350
processes that aren't
present otherwise.

00:16:58.350 --> 00:17:04.480
In fact, we learned that last
week, with the eyes study when

00:17:04.480 --> 00:17:09.400
we learned that people are more
pro-social, more likely

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:13.520
to engage in morally normative
behavior, when they're

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:16.910
presented visually, with eyes,
in part, because it awakens

00:17:16.910 --> 00:17:20.878
and activates a kind of social
understanding which all of us

00:17:20.878 --> 00:17:21.364
have.

00:17:21.364 --> 00:17:24.020
So the first difference between
the bottom and the top

00:17:24.020 --> 00:17:29.130
is that the bottom one invokes
sociality, whereas the top one

00:17:29.130 --> 00:17:31.490
is purely abstract.

00:17:31.490 --> 00:17:33.830
And the second difference
between the bottom and top is,

00:17:33.830 --> 00:17:37.280
of course, that this is
a normative rule.

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:39.810
It's about how things
ought to be.

00:17:39.810 --> 00:17:41.700
Whereas this is a descriptive
rule.

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:45.220
It's about how things are.

00:17:45.220 --> 00:17:49.046
So the lesson that we can take
away from the Wason selection

00:17:49.046 --> 00:17:51.937
task, for those of you who are
interested in it, there have

00:17:51.937 --> 00:17:54.510
been thousands and thousands
of variations done on it,

00:17:54.510 --> 00:17:57.660
which are extremely interesting
in sorting out

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:01.372
exactly where people are good
and not so good at the task.

00:18:01.372 --> 00:18:06.000
The lesson that we can take
away from it is the lesson

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.903
that has been emphasized
throughout this lecture and

00:18:09.903 --> 00:18:11.450
the previous one.

00:18:11.450 --> 00:18:16.460
That we have ways of processing
information that

00:18:16.460 --> 00:18:20.408
don't merely track formal
properties.

00:18:20.408 --> 00:18:25.640
And some of those ways of
processing information involve

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:32.140
bringing on line, so to speak,
what Plato would call parts of

00:18:32.140 --> 00:18:35.300
the soul which had not
been previously

00:18:35.300 --> 00:18:39.410
attentive to the situation.

00:18:39.410 --> 00:18:40.590
Now--

00:18:40.590 --> 00:18:42.550
Is there a question
